SIMPLE: effort
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Effort
<hw>Ef"fort</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>effort</ets>,
OF. <ets>esfort</ets>, for <ets>esfors</ets>, <ets>esforz</ets>, fr.
<ets>esforcier</ets>. See <er>Efforce</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>An
exertion of strength or power, whether physical or mental, in performing
an act or aiming at an object; more or less strenuous endeavor; struggle
directed to the accomplishment of an object; <as>as, an <ex>effort</ex>
to scale a wall</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>We prize the stronger <qex>effort</qex> of his power.</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Mech.)</fld> <def>A force acting on a body in the
direction of its motion.</def> <rj><au>Rankine.</au></rj></p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Endeavor; exertion; struggle; strain; straining;
attempt; trial; essay. See <er>Attempt</er>.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Effort</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Effort
<hw>Ef"fort</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To stimulate.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> ⟦ldquo⟧He <xex>efforted</xex> his spirits.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Fuller.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>effortful</ent>⟦br⟧
